nstitutional order and set the stage for presidential supremacy. The presidency, Alford argues, is now more than imperial: it is an elective dictatorship. Providing both an overview and a systematic analysis of the new regime, he objectively demonstrates that it does not meet even the minimum requirements of the rule of law. At this critical juncture in American democracy, Permanent State of Emergency alerts the public to the structural transformation of the state and reiterates the importance of the constitutional limits of the American presidency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExecutive powerxUnited States. 0aExecutive powerzUnited States. 0aRule of lawxUnited States. 0aRule of lawzUnited States. 0aWar and emergency powersxUnited States. 0aWar and emergency powerszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077354920340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773549203423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773549203/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles